Through the use of HR-TEM, morphological examination of synthesized N-C-dots was carried out. HRTEM micrographs for N-G1h, N-G2h, and N-G3h are depicted in Fig. 2
                         (a), (b), & (c), correspondingly. HRTEM study of synthesized N-doped-C-dots revealed approximately spherical morphology. The mean particle size for N-G1h is 9.97 nm. Particle size reduces as pyrolysis time is increased. N-G3h has the smallest mean particle size which is in the range of 3.06–9.49 nm (Table 1
                        ). The particle size of the synthesized N-G1h and N-G3h, differs noticeably. The confined variation of size of NPs of N-G1h, N-G2h, along with N-G3h is depicted by the histograms in Fig. 2 (d), (e), and (f), correspondingly.

The optical characteristics i.e., UV–vis absorption spectra and band gap (E

                           g
                        ) of synthesized N-G1h, N-G2h, and N-G3h are examined by UV–Vis investigation (Fig. 3
                        ). Absorption peaks in the range 230–235 nm are associated to π-π* transition of CN and CC bonds [31]. UV–vis absorbance spectra for resultant N-doped-C-dots demonstrated no additional absorbance in visible region. This finding indicated no production of any other types of nanocarbon, which typically absorbed at higher wavelengths upon the partial carbonization of the precursor i.e., garlic [32]. The band gap value for N-G1h, N-G2h and N-G3h are determined from Tauc's plot which are 4.21, 4.14 and 4.03 eV, respectively. It shows that N-G3h has the lowest E

                           g
                         [33,34].
